μὲν τροπῆς διὰ τὸ φύσει θνητὸν ἐγγινομένης, τῆς δὲ ἐλευθερίας διὰ τὴν τοῦ Θεοῦ θεραπείαν ἐπιγινομένης. Schneckenburger takes τροπή here in Philo's sense, and translates obumbratio quae oritur ex inconstantia necturae. This gives a very good sense, ‘ overshadowing of mutability,' as one might speak of ‘ an overshadowing of disgrace ' : no changes in this lower world can cast a shadow on the nnchanging Fount of light. Or we may take τροπῆς as a qualitative genitive, and interpret as Stolz does, after Luther, ‘keine abwechselnde Verdunkelung.' Beyschlag maintains that this would require τροπὴ (1ἰττ-οο-κιοὶο-μοιτος,1 but why may not ⁶ overshadowing of change ⁷ serve to express ⁶ changing shadow' (Le. an overshadowing which changes the face of the sun), just as well as ⁴ a hearer of forgetfulness ’ in ver. 25 to express ‘a forgetful hearer' or ‘ the world of wickedness ' in iii. 6 to express ‘ the wicked world ’2 The meaning of the passage will then be ‘God is alike incapable of change in his own nature (παραλλαγή) and incapable of being changed by the action of others (ἀποσκίασμα).’ 011 the unchangeableness of God compare Mal. iii. 6, Heb. xiii. 8. It is on this doctrine that Plato founds his argument against the possibility of a Divine Incarnation (Hel). ii. 380 foll.). See comment. Spitta takes τροπή of the Sun's invisible return from west to east and ἀποσκίασμα of the darkness of night.
